  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         = Z_r^{pq}/(B_r^{pq}\cap  Z_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.2}       ]]></fr:tex>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>987</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>1.3.1</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> be a differential complex of objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>, endowed with a filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>.
    The filtration is said to be <fr:em>biregular</fr:em> if it induces a finite filtration on each component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>We recall the definition of the terms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}(K,F)]]></fr:tex>, or simply <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex>, of the spectral sequence defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>.
    We set
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       Z_r^{pq}       = \operatorname {Ker}(d\colon  F^p(K^{p+q})\to  F^{p+q+1}/F^{p+r}(K^{p+q+1}))     ]]></fr:tex>
    and dually we define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex> by the formula
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq}       = \operatorname {Coker}(d\colon  F^{p-r+1}(K^{p+q+1})\to  K^{p+q}/F^{p+1}(K^{p+q})).     ]]></fr:tex>
    These formulas still make sense for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r=\infty ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>We note that the use here of the notation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex> is different to that of Godement <fr:link type="local" href="G1958.xml" addr="G1958" title="Topologie algébrique et théorie des faisceaux">[G1958]</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>We have, by definition:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>498</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.1.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_r^{pq}         = \operatorname {Im}(Z_r^{pq}\to  K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>499</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.1.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         = Z_r^{pq}/(B_r^{pq}\cap  Z_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>500</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.3.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.1.3</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         = \operatorname {Ker}(K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq}\to  K^{p+q}/(Z_r^{pq}+B_r^{pq})).       \tag{1.3.1.3}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    We can thus write

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>501</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.4.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.1.4</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \begin {aligned}           B_r^{p\bullet }\cap  Z_r^{p\bullet }           &\coloneqq  (dF^{p-r+1}+F^{p+1}) \cap  (d^{-1}F^{p+r}\cap  F^p)         \\&= (dF^{p-r+1}\cap  F^p) + (F^{p+1}\cap  d^{-1}F^{p+r})         \end {aligned}       \tag{1.3.1.4}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[dF^{p-r+1}\subset  d^{-1}F^{p+r}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^{p+1}\subset  F^p]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r<\infty ]]></fr:tex>, the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r]]></fr:tex> form a complex graded by the degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p-r(p+q)]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{r+1}]]></fr:tex> can be expressed as the cohomology of this complex:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>502</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.5</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.5.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.1.5</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_{r+1}^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}(E_r^{p-r,q+r-1} \xrightarrow {d_r} E_r^{pq} \xrightarrow {d_r} E_r^{p+r,q-r+1}).       \tag{1.3.1.5}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r=0]]></fr:tex>, we have

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>503</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.6</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.6.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.1.6</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_0^{\bullet \bullet }         = \operatorname {Gr}_F^\bullet (K^\bullet ).       \tag{1.3.1.6}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>988</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>1.3.4</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
      The morphisms in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="1.3.3.2" /> form a morphism of graded complexes from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_0(\operatorname {Dec}(K))]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1(K)]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
      This morphism induces an isomorphism on cohomology.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(iii) &quot;">
      This morphism induces step-by-step (via <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.5" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.5.xml" taxon="Equation" number="1.3.1.5" />) isomorphisms of graded complexes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(\operatorname {Dec}(K))\xrightarrow {\sim } E_{r+1}(K)]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\geqslant 1]]></fr:tex>).
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>

  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>951</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#290</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-290.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F']]></fr:tex> be the filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> defined by
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         {F'}^p(K^n)         = \operatorname {Dec}(F)^{p-n}(K^n)         = Z_1^{p,n-p}.       ]]></fr:tex>
      We trivially have isomorphisms

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>952</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.3.4.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           E_r^{p,n-p}(\operatorname {Dec}(K))           = E_{r+1}^{p+n,-p}(K,F')         \tag{1.3.4.1}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      that are compatible with the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> and with <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.5" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.5.xml" taxon="Equation" number="1.3.1.5" />.
      The map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> comes from <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="1.3.4.1" /> and from the identity map
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         (K,F') \to  (K,F).       ]]></fr:tex>
      This proves (i), and it remains to show that, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\geqslant 2]]></fr:tex>,
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_r^{pq}(K,F')         \xrightarrow {\sim } E_r^{pq}(K,F).       ]]></fr:tex>
      We have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \begin {aligned}           Z_r^{pq}(K,F')           &= Z_r^{pq}(K,F)           \qquad \text {for }r\geqslant 1         \\Z_r^{pq}(K,F') \cap  B_r^{pq}(K,F')           &= Z_r^{pq}(K,F) \cap  B_r^{pq}(K,F)           \qquad \text {for }r\geqslant 2         \end {aligned}       ]]></fr:tex>
      and we can then apply <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="1.3.1.2" />.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>989</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>1.3.8</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p><fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="1.3.1.2" /> identifies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex> with a quotient of a sub-object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K^{p+q}]]></fr:tex>.
    The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex> term is thusly given by endowing with a filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_d]]></fr:tex> induced by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, called the <fr:em>first direct filtration</fr:em>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
